gui-speedtest (1.1.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Ookla backend: availability check now verifies the `speedtest` binary
    identifies as Ookla's official CLI (parsing `--version` output for
    "Ookla"). The Ubuntu `speedtest-cli` package (sivel/speedtest-cli)
    also installs as `speedtest` but accepts different arguments — running
    our Ookla argv against it previously produced empty JSON output and
    a confusing "Could not parse" error. Now the picker simply omits
    Ookla when the wrong binary is on PATH.
  * M-Lab backend: latency now measured as the WebSocket handshake round-trip
    (create_connection timing) instead of HTTPS HEAD against the wss://
    endpoint. M-Lab servers return 405 Method Not Allowed for HEAD, so every
    sample failed in v1.0.x. Latency now shows real numbers.
  * M-Lab backend: client IP / ISP / location now enriched via ipify +
    ipwho.is so the GUI reports your actual connection instead of
    "Unknown". Mirrors the Cloudflare fallback and OVH patterns.
  * GUI: Cancel button during a running test. Start → "Cancel" (destructive
    styling) while running → reverts to "Run Again" on completion. Calls
    backend.cancel() which terminates Ookla subprocesses immediately; for
    HTTP-based backends the current chunk finishes or times out before the
    worker thread exits (phase-boundary check on self.cancelled).
  * Packaging: AppStream metainfo.xml (data/io.github.mmhfarooque.GuiSpeedTest.metainfo.xml)
    installed to /usr/share/metainfo/. Enables the app to appear with a
    proper description in GNOME Software, KDE Discover, and other
    AppStream-indexing software stores.
  * Packaging: build-appimage.sh now implements the full python-appimage ->
    extract AppDir -> linuxdeploy-plugin-gtk -> AppImage pipeline. Gated
    behind repo variable APPIMAGE_READY=1 until end-to-end tested.

 -- Mahmud Farooque <farooque7@gmail.com>  Sat, 18 Apr 2026 15:30:00 +0600

gui-speedtest (1.0.1-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Security: bump websocket-client floor to >=1.8 (closes CVE-2024-5569
    ReDoS in Sec-WebSocket-Protocol parser); cap upper bound at <3 so a
    future 2.x major can't silently break the M-Lab backend.
  * Security: cap M-Lab WebSocket frame payloads at 16 MiB via create_connection
    max_size kwarg — defends against a malicious/misbehaving server driving
    the process OOM with a single oversized frame.
  * Packaging: switch debian/source/format from 3.0 (native) to 3.0 (quilt)
    to resolve the conflict with a -1 Debian revision in changelog.
  * Packaging: PEP 639 SPDX license migration deferred — Ubuntu 24.04 ships
    setuptools 68.x which rejects the `license = "..."` string form.
    Revisit when Ubuntu 26.04 (setuptools 75+) is the .deb build baseline.
  * Packaging: classifiers bumped to Development Status 5 - Production/Stable;
    explicit Python 3.10/3.11/3.12/3.13 classifiers added.
  * Packaging: switch setuptools package discovery to find with include
    backends* — future sub-packages get picked up automatically.
  * Packaging: pin gir1.2-gtk-4.0 (>= 4.12) so CssProvider.load_from_string
    is guaranteed available at runtime.
  * CI: migrate to Node 24 action majors — checkout@v6, setup-python@v6,
    upload-artifact@v7, download-artifact@v8, action-gh-release@v3. Clears
    the Node.js 20 deprecation warning ahead of the 2026-06-02 deadline.
  * CI: Python matrix 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13 on lint+smoke jobs.
  * Polish: refresh Chrome UA 120 -> 140 in the browser spoof string;
    simplify _run_cli_latency return (dead var); document LibreSpeed
    _validate_url DNS check as informational (TOCTOU window exists, not
    a security boundary); drop unused WHEEL= line in build-appimage.sh.

 -- Mahmud Farooque <farooque7@gmail.com>  Sat, 18 Apr 2026 14:45:00 +0600

